Minimal correct fix — move the Escape listener to the document and add initial focus (which also makes the "focus-trapped" docstring honest). In OutboxDrawer (src/components/layout/sync-status-island.tsx), convert it to use a ref + effect instead of the in-subtree onKeyDown:

  const panelRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);
  useEffect(() => {
    const onKey = (e: KeyboardEvent) => { if (e.key === "Escape") onClose(); };
    document.addEventListener("keydown", onKey);
    const prev = document.activeElement as HTMLElement | null;
    panelRef.current?.focus();              // move focus into the drawer on open
    return () => {
      document.removeEventListener("keydown", onKey);
      prev?.focus?.();                       // restore focus to the pill on close
    };
  }, [onClose]);

Then drop the `onKeyDown={...}` from the portal root <div> (lines 87-89), and add `ref={panelRef} tabIndex={-1}` to the <aside> panel (line 98) so it can receive the initial focus. Ship the missing regression test in the same commit: render <SyncStatus/>, click the pill, fireEvent.keyDown(document, {key:'Escape'}), assert the dialog is gone — this FAILS on the current code (handler on a sibling subtree) and passes after the fix.

Better (larger, optional) fix: route the panel through the shared Dialog (src/components/ui/dialog.tsx), which already owns document-level Escape, scroll lock, initial focus, focus trap, and focus restore — eliminating the duplicated, half-built focus logic and making the docstring's "focus-trapped" claim real for free.
